::section{#introduction}
::meta
type: introduction
summary: "Introduction to Urban Heat Islands and their historical link to altered precipitation patterns."
::

# Introduction

The Urban Heat Island (UHI) effect refers to the phenomenon where urban 
areas experience significantly higher temperatures than their rural 
surroundings @cite{oke1982}. Recent studies indicate that this thermal 
anomaly can disrupt local wind patterns and enhance convective 
precipitation @cite{shepherd2005}.

::endsection


::section{#methods}
::meta
type: methods
summary: "Data sources from NEXRAD radar and urban temperature sensors."
::

# Methodology

We utilized 10 years of NEXRAD Level II radar data to track precipitation 
events. Temperature data were obtained from high-density urban sensor 
networks and satellite-derived land surface temperature (LST) maps.

::endsection


::section{#results}
::meta
type: results
summary: "Analysis of precipitation intensity and frequency downwind of urban areas."
depends_on: ["#methods"]
::

# Results

Our analysis focused on the "urban-induced rainfall" (UIR) occurring within 
50 km of the city center.

::chart{#tbl-rainfall-comparison}
::title Summer precipitation intensity: Urban vs. Rural
::interpretation
The data shows a clear increase in both mean and peak precipitation 
intensity in urban areas compared to rural control sites. Miami exhibits 
the strongest UHI-precipitation coupling, with a 25% increase in 
late-afternoon rain volume.
::
| City | Urban Avg Rain (mm/h) | Rural Avg Rain (mm/h) | Variance (%) |
|------|-----------------------|-----------------------|--------------|
| Miami | 12.4 | 9.8 | +26.5 |
| Houston | 10.5 | 8.9 | +18.0 |
| New Orleans | 11.2 | 10.1 | +10.9 |
::endchart

::diagram{#fig-uhi-mechanism}
::type flowchart
::description
This diagram illustrates the thermodynamic mechanism by which urban heat 
leads to increased rainfall: Surface heating -> Convective updraft -> 
Moisture convergence -> Precipitation.
::
```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Urban Surface Heating] --> B[Convective Updraft]
    B --> C[Moisture Convergence]
    C --> D[Precipitation]
```
::enddiagram

::endsection


::section{#conclusion}
::meta
type: conclusion
summary: "Conclusions on urban planning and climate adaptation."
depends_on: ["#results"]
::

# Conclusion

Urban centers act as significant drivers of local weather modification. 
Integrating "cool city" strategies (e.g., green roofs, reflective pavements) 
may help mitigate not only temperatures but also the risk of 
urban flash flooding induced by UHI.

::endsection
